MZANSI is on alert: a deadly disease known as Listeriosis has broken out. Last week, Health Minister Dr Aaron Motsoaledi announced that a shocking 557 cases of Listeriosis were reported in the past year, with the majority occurring in Gauteng, of whom 36 died. But how do you protect yourself against this dangerous bacteria? What is Listeriosis? According to food safety guidelines, Listeria is bacteria found in soil, water and vegetation. It can also be found in some animals, including poultry and cattle. Raw milks and foods made from raw milk can also carry the Listeria bacteria. Symptoms People should seek medical attention if they experience the following symptoms: Treatment The treatment of listeriosis is usually based on symptoms and depends on the severity of infection. The majority of people infected by listeria recover within seven days. However, those with a compromised immune system such as older adults, infants or pregnant women require urgent medical care. A severe infection may require feeding antibiotics and fluids through an IV drip. Home remedies Prevention 5 Deadly Body Odours You Should Never Ignore 8 STIs You've Probably Never Heard Of!!! This is why you should never let your dog lick your mouth These content links are provided by Content.ad. Both Content.ad and the web site upon which the links are displayed may receive compensation when readers click on these links. Some of the content you are redirected to may be sponsored content. View our privacy policy here. To learn how you can use Content.ad to drive visitors to your content or add this service to your site, please contact us at info@content.ad. Family-Friendly Content  Only recommend family-friendly content Website owners select the type of content that appears in our units. However, if you would like to ensure that Content.ad always displays family-friendly content on this device, regardless of what site you are on, check the option below. Learn More